postcontent:
I can't confirm on the company who imported the rifle, but I wouldn't be far off saying it might be Century Arms.  As with most of the Romanian WASRs, they are plagued with the canted FSB and RGB; this rifle has a slight cant to the right. Rifle was sighted to compensate. 

This rifle comes with two sets of wood furniture: laminated wood and Romanian SAR-1 hardwood with palm swell. 
Barrel is Chrome lined, threaded and equipped with a slant brake. 
Two different slings: Romanian leather and Chinese Green canvas with leather. 
Three pistol grips: Two Romanian Bakelite with inward diamond checkering and one black U.S. made. 
No cleaning rod.
Two 30 round steel magazines: One Romanian with Finnish floor plate and one Chinese. 
Fire trigger assembly has been substituted for a Tapco G2 single hook assembly.
Safety on the rifle was disabled before ownership and does not affect operation.
Rifle could use new bluing.
Lastly, this rifle has received one of the nicer "single-to-double" stack mag-well conversions that I've seen.  Nothing about the work was jagged and I've had minimum wobble. ***It varies between the magazines used***. 
Front trunnion, gas tube, bolt assembly and dust cover are all number matching; spring is stamped, but with another number. 

Rifle has been disassembled, cleaned, sprayed with Corrosion X, re-oiled with M-Pro-7 and the bore has been wiped with M-Pro-7 Copper Remover. 

I rather sell the rifle than trade, but I'll entertain all offers. If value is slightly greater, +cash on my end.
I am particularly interested in the following:
Kimber .22 rifles; H&K .45 USP; full size 1911s; .40 compacts.

title: For Sale:  The model 1873 Winchester
postcontent:
Referred to as the "Gun that Won the West", the Winchester model 1873 was manufactured in the following calibers: .44-40, .38-40 and .32-20. Modern replicas are offered in those calibers and also the .45 long colt, though it wasn't originally offered in that caliber.

Something many don't know, John M. Browning used an 1873 to make his first prototype automatic firing gun. After seeing what a muzzle blast could do to a patch of grass, he tested it and found he was correct. The muzzle blast from the gun was heavy enough to be harnessed, so he took a flapper and attached it to the muzzle and the lever and invented his first automatic rifle.
